elements.instruction:
Flexible parts and body:
Move the flexible parts / body to its maximal positions and observe whether the product is still stable or not.

If there is a load-bearing part or surface:
Apply a force at the center line of the load-bearing surface.
If no force specified by the client, use the following:
Length >= 1600 mm, apply 600 N (60 kg);
800 mm < Length < 1600 mm, apply 450 N (45 kg);
Length <= 800 mm, apply 300 N (30 kg);

The weights should not come closer than 100 mm from the edges of the load-bearing surface (unless the design does not allow it).

1. To make sure the surface is clean before the test.
2. Use a strip of pressure-sensitive tape (3M 500 for instance) and apply it firmly on the whole area to be tested: artwork, logo, marking or the area specified by the client;
3. Press it by hand on the surface so that the tape is properly stuck, with no bubble or wrinkle;
4. Remove the tape in 0.5-1s with an angle close to 60 degrees, rapidly but not jerked.
5. Repeat this operation 3 times in the same area, the used tape should be cut off.

1. Rub the marking or printing with a dry white cotton cloth 10 times over a 10cm distance 
2. Repeat the test with a white cotton cloth (soaked with purified water; 
3. Repeat with a white cotton cloth soaked with petroleum spirit or 92-95% alcohol.

1. Connect the toilet to a assembled tank;
2. Supply water to the tank at a pressure of 0.4MPa, until the water reaches the water line;
3. Put 100 balls (0.38mm diameter and of 0.85-0.9gram/cm3 density) into the bowl of toilet;
4. Flush and observe if the balls are effectively flushed away.
